      {
        "id": "58d38980bb0b1ca53ed3eb71e072d2b4ddbeedaa",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1581,
          "name": "Michael Morris",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "michael.morris@ericsson.com",
          "username": "mmis"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-30 09:49:59.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIf the need arises to change to use a database for all users then the existing implementation class can be updated without impacting on the users. I would however consider that it is not necessarily a bad thing to impact all uses for such a change, so as each use can consider if the changed implementation is appropriate for that use. \nAside from that, and I accept this is subjective, I think an interface should be just an interface, i.e an abstraction. Adding implementation code into the interface dilutes the concept of it being an abstraction.\n\nIf non singleton behaviour is required for a particular use, then a separate implementation of the interface can be provided that does not have the singleton behaviour, with the users free to pick the implementation that suits their needs.\nIn a scenario where somebody could instantiate a factory directly using new, then the static final factory member will contain a reference to the wrong factory for the classes instantiated by that factory, leaving the door open for errors\n\nRegarding the \"Indexed\" names proliferating in user code, perhaps we could come up with a name that would read better, maybe CachingXXXFactory or SingletonCachingXXXFactory or...",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "33711116053a633a1aa7a738dd035e3321ca8c85",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 57,
          "name": "Pamela Dragosh",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pd1248@att.com",
          "username": "pdragosh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-30 12:18:38.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nWe need to resolve this asap. We need the endpoint code for the other repos. I don't think I understand your comments Jorge.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "5f863ee969d21caadc83bc386412d0d5e40b9271",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-30 14:33:49.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nMichael, the fact that somebody may or may not like final static data members in an interface does not justify design changes.   A simple change of the “interface” to an “abstract class” would do it in that case.    I have an issue with the scope of changes as the original design is altered and constrained.   Again, to summary my thoughts in a list:\n\n1.\tIssue 1:  A factory implementation is now a singleton.   With the current changes, factory implementations are singletons, they have a \"getInstance()\" and there can only be used in a singleton way.   This is a change from the original implementation and it has constrained the original design intent, as the for example IndexedUebTopicSinkFactory and all those factories could be instantiated as many as you want with “new”, and it may make sense to have them as such, when the PDP-D supports same topics, in different  sever clusters, ie. topic X in host 1, and topic X in host 2.   Right now, only one instance on per application space is accessible.   This is a change and a constraint in the design. \n2.\tIssue 2:  Users of the code were coding to an interface, now the implementation leaks into their code.\n3.\tIssue 3:  Several hundreds of unnecessary lines of code inspections have been added.   Only thing necessary would have been to change the package name in the import, and change the pom.xml to realize the moving of the code change.     This work goes far beyond that, and impacts additional hundreds of lines of codes on the users of these classes.\n4.\tIssue 3:  Readability by users of class decreases, as the original intent that the implementation details get hidden, now the “Indexed” .. etc .. has to carry forward in all the uses.   Further, all name changes, have to be carried onwards by any other project outside policy that uses it, etc ..\n\nI am sorry I didn’t catch this early, but was just thinking this was a plain routine move of code.   \n\nI understand  that we want to merge the code in the base, and you’re going on vacations.  Not sure, what’s the best way to move forward, but I’m open to solutions to merge this with some contingencies on some work being done on as a follow up on this regard as a consequence of my comments.",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "685aa2b3e21e57404d825e18fb38fabd2b20716e",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 57,
          "name": "Pamela Dragosh",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pd1248@att.com",
          "username": "pdragosh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-30 14:52:07.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nOk, philosophy aside. The agreement was to do a copy/move of the code. So let's honor that. We don't want to break Jorge's code. Reverting seems too much, would just re-working the code back to its original intent be enough? policy/common first and then policy/drools-pdp? the policy/engine fix is easy. Does that sound ok?",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "22cd6c762ad0d5cce21f689f6fbe95d4b9dbbe58",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 1581,
          "name": "Michael Morris",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "michael.morris@ericsson.com",
          "username": "mmis"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-30 14:55:36.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nOk, i will rework to be a simple move with no changes beyond what is necessary for the move",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "ca49b9c57636d1b57aeca54768fbd87a978fa37a",
